The Diseases of Globalization
Globalization is facing its toughest test ever.
Tensions are brewing everywhere.
The majority of Black Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
War now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in just a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Some regions of the world have reaped great benefits from globalization, notably East Asia and China in recent years.
Some regions, however, have reaped only meager benefits, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they struggle with.
The slow growth of Africa, assert American leaders, is caused by the ineptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades while many Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of governance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and thus large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to be more performant than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more performant than countries that are far from major markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If wealthy countries pay little attention to these structural problems, the gaps between the winners and the losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift responsibility onto unfortunate countries by claiming that they are somehow culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than that offered by wealthy countries, and particularly America.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the fundamental needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their own country.
But in others, an honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to raise sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Instead of seeing wealthy countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require wealthy countries to provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation strikingly.
Disease control requires a health system capable of providing life-saving medicines and basic preventive services such as mosquito nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount is just a grain of sand for wealthy countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the capacity of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even if Malawi is well governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases unless it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of scolding the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for every country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that slow their growth and economic development.
In some regions like the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and internet connectivity in order to help these remote regions establish productive connections with the world.
Wealthy countries must contribute to financing these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges are disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main issues are lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific problems.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The one-size-fits-all ideology of the Washington Consensus is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinkers of the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
